@node "tooltypes" "Tooltypes"
@{b}Tooltypes@{ub}

  The following tooltypes are accepted and initialized by AHelp:

  WBSCREEN      Normally Dr.Hpgl tries to look for the screen
                named PageStream4.  This tooltype tells that,
                using the Workbench screen beside any pubscreen.

  XASPECT=      These tooltypes especially for those who are still
  YASPECT=      using Amiga Classic native screenmodes.
                Some resolutions, like PAL640x256 has pixel aspect
                2:1, but PAL 640x512 has 1:1. So these variables
                lets you correct the display aspect.

  REAL_BOUND    This will adjust the origo to the top left corner
                of the loaded drawing.

  PRECISION=    Multiple factor of the integer conversion.
                See the Prefs section of the page @{"Using" link "ques"}

  DEFNUMSTEPS=  The minimal number of sections to build a curve.

  MAXNUMSTEPS=  The maximal number of sections to build a curve.

  DEFDELTA=     The maximal length of a curve section's straigth
                line on the screen output.

  DELTAPLOT=    The same as above, but this for plotting.

  Tooltypes in brackets are inactive.
 
@endnode

@node "install" "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

  To install Dr.Hpgl simply copy its folder to wherever you like.
  If your system does not start the Arexx interpreter at startup,
  you have to start it manually from the Wb:System folder before
  using Dr.Hpgl.
  However RexxMast is in the WbStartup drawer is recommended.

  If there are any problems, please contact @{"me" link "autor"}.

@endnode

@node "wasmacht" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  Let`s have a short visit to the past...

  ...back in the '80s there was a DTP program called PageStream2,
  which made very efficient and good job creating various DTP
  projects on the Amiga. That program has got a HPGL printer driver
  let the user to use plotter like machines, especially vinyl cutters.

  From version 3.0 PageStream made a big step towards the professional
  DTP market, but the HPGL support is missed. At this time PageStream
  has a decent home on 6 platforms, and still be very productive to
  work with it.

  Dr.Hpgl was born from the need to using a vinyl cutter connected to
  a PageStream equipped Amiga.

  At this time Dr.Hpgl can get any non-bitmap design from PageStream
  (or can load it in DR2D vector format) and send it to a plotter in
  a manner that plotters are understand.

  Development is focused on vinyl cutters, so there is no possibilities
  for special plotter tasks, e.g. exchange pens.

@endnode

